### Workarounds thought of for developers in the meantime (both gross):

1. JavaScript function that subscribes to the window error events and reloads the page when the user clicks something and gets the specific "There is no event handler associated with this event." error message. This is a bad user experience in addition to being very hacky.
2. Call a GetCircuitId .NET function from javascript that returns the current circuit id. In normal operation this will return a good value, but if the circuit is still starting up or is in the broken state it will return an empty string. Nice in that it isn't as bad of a user experience, but the race condition with the circuit starting up returning empty string just like the bugged state is not good.

